  "macro_segments": [
    {
      "title": "Tosfos on Mechila (Forgiveness) of Debt and Contemporary Financial Mechanisms",
      "display_title": "Mechila & Debt Markets",
      "timestamp": "00:18",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Introduction to the Tosfos discussion on selling debt and mechila",
          "display_title": "Debt Sale Problem",
          "timestamp": "00:18"
        },
        {
          "title": "The example of Michael buying a debt from the lecturer, and the problem of mechila destroying the market",
          "display_title": "Market Destruction Issue",
          "timestamp": "00:28"
        },
        {
          "title": "Tosfos's response: Four mechanisms to ensure mechila does not occur (mashkon, arevut, shvua, neder)",
          "display_title": "Tosfos Solutions",
          "timestamp": "01:00"
        },
        {
          "title": "Historical significance: Tosfos recognizing the modern financial system centuries before its development",
          "display_title": "Historical Significance",
          "timestamp": "05:09"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Takanas Usha and the Debate over Kinyan Peiros vs. Kinyan Haguf in Nichsei Milugs",
      "display_title": "Takanas Usha Debate",
      "timestamp": "05:16",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Introduction to the issue: Can a woman sell her nichsei milugs, and does kinyan peiros give ownership?",
          "display_title": "Woman's Sales Rights",
          "timestamp": "05:16"
        },
        {
          "title": "First braita: Slaves of milugs go free by shein v'ayin only for the woman, establishing she is the owner",
          "display_title": "First Braita",
          "timestamp": "05:21"
        },
        {
          "title": "Second braita: Neither the man nor the woman can free slaves by shein v'ayin, suggesting takanas Usha exists",
          "display_title": "Second Braita",
          "timestamp": "05:32"
        },
        {
          "title": "Gemara's analysis: The debate may be about takanas Usha or about kinyan peiros",
          "display_title": "Gemara Analysis",
          "timestamp": "06:00"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rava's principle: Shichrur (freeing) and hekdesh undo liens because they change the object's identity fundamentally",
          "display_title": "Rava's Principle",
          "timestamp": "08:22"
        },
        {
          "title": "Application to slaves: The woman can free a slave through shein v'ayin even after takanas Usha because shichrur changes identity",
          "display_title": "Shichru & Identity",
          "timestamp": "12:13"
        },
        {
          "title": "Alternative explanation: The braisos debate kinyan peiros kekinyan haguf, not takanas Usha",
          "display_title": "Kinyan Peiros Debate",
          "timestamp": "13:38"
        },
        {
          "title": "Ameimar's teaching: A husband and wife cannot jointly sell nichsei milugs because neither has sufficient owner status",
          "display_title": "Ameimar Teaching",
          "timestamp": "23:39"
        },
        {
          "title": "Connection to shein v'ayin: One cannot free a half-slave or a slave owned jointly; full ownership is required",
          "display_title": "Full Ownership Req.",
          "timestamp": "25:23"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Boshet (Embarrassment) and Fixed Amounts vs. Case-by-Case Assessment",
      "display_title": "Boshet Damages",
      "timestamp": "27:42",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Introduction to boshet: Unlike other damages, boshet is assessed case-by-case per the mishnah's principle",
          "display_title": "Boshet Principle",
          "timestamp": "27:42"
        },
        {
          "title": "Specific actions and their boshet payments: tokeia (ear), sotra (face), back of hand, pulling hair, spitting, uncovering a woman's hair",
          "display_title": "Fixed Amounts List",
          "timestamp": "29:10"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Akiva's resolution: Even the poor have the dignity of royalty (Abraham, Isaac, Jacob), so everyone deserves maximum boshet",
          "display_title": "Rabbi Akiva's Dignity",
          "timestamp": "31:39"
        },
        {
          "title": "Story of a woman whose hair was uncovered in the marketplace: She accepted 400 zuz, but when given a chance, she uncovered her own hair for oil",
          "display_title": "Hair Uncovering Story",
          "timestamp": "34:18"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Akiva's ruling: Objective value of shame (400 zuz) does not change based on the victim's willingness to shame herself",
          "display_title": "Objective Value",
          "timestamp": "36:00"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Witness as Judge (Ed Na'aseh Dayan) and Assessment of Instruments of Injury",
      "display_title": "Witness as Judge",
      "timestamp": "40:29",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "The legal problem: Can a person who witnesses an event also serve as judge in that case?",
          "display_title": "Core Problem",
          "timestamp": "40:29"
        },
        {
          "title": "Baraita: Rabbi Tarfon says some must be witnesses, others judges; Rabbi Akiva says witnessing itself disqualifies you",
          "display_title": "Tarfon vs Akiva",
          "timestamp": "41:55"
        },
        {
          "title": "Gemara's resolution: If witnessed during day, it's like accepting testimony; if at night, must wait for formal witnesses",
          "display_title": "Day vs Night Rule",
          "timestamp": "43:38"
        },
        {
          "title": "Alternative explanation: The judge is saying he holds like Rabbi Yose HaGlili's position, not that he personally witnessed",
          "display_title": "Alt Explanation",
          "timestamp": "45:21"
        },
        {
          "title": "Shimon HaTeimani's principle: The instrument of injury (e.g., fist, stone) must be assessed by witnesses and judges",
          "display_title": "Instrument Rule",
          "timestamp": "46:06"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Akiva's objection: The beis din cannot always directly see the instrument (e.g., fall from building), so judges must rely on witnesses",
          "display_title": "Akiva Objection",
          "timestamp": "47:31"
        },
        {
          "title": "Resolution: Only things that can be assessed by witnesses (like a fist) are needed; if the instrument is lost, the defendant goes free",
          "display_title": "Witness Assessment",
          "timestamp": "48:45"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Shor Tam and Shor Mu'ad: Order of Judgment in Capital and Monetary Cases",
      "display_title": "Shor Tam & Mu'ad",
      "timestamp": "51:19",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Baraita: A tam ox that kills and damages requires capital judgment first; a mu'ad ox requires monetary judgment first",
          "display_title": "Judgment Order Rule",
          "timestamp": "51:19"
        },
        {
          "title": "The principle: If capital judgment is given first, you cannot later give monetary judgment (for tam ox)",
          "display_title": "Tam Ox Rule",
          "timestamp": "51:43"
        },
        {
          "title": "The problem: Why should order matter for a mu'ad ox, which pays from its own body or owner's pocket either way?",
          "display_title": "Mu'ad Problem",
          "timestamp": "52:00"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rava's source: The Rabbis hold that beis din must assess the ox's capability to injure; this assessment becomes moot once it is condemned",
          "display_title": "Rava's Source",
          "timestamp": "53:00"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rava's explanation: Once a shor nesakel is condemned, you cannot delay execution to inspect it for monetary judgment, as this causes tzaar to the ox",
          "display_title": "Execution Delay",
          "timestamp": "53:52"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
